docs/ANALYTICS_TRACKING_PLAN.md:59:- Compare GA4 diagnostic completions with first-party diagnostic rows; investigate large mismatches rather than forcing the numbers to match.
docs/submission/DEVPOST_COPY.md:17:Find the connection a word is missing—then rebuild it in 15 focused minutes.
docs/submission/DEVPOST_COPY.md:21:15Loop is an adaptive English vocabulary coach for Korean upper-elementary and first-year middle-school learners. It checks four separate connections—written word to meaning, sound to word, word in context, and meaning to active recall—then uses the learner's evidence to decide what should be reviewed next.
docs/submission/DEVPOST_COPY.md:41:15Loop started with a parent problem.
docs/submission/DEVPOST_COPY.md:43:My child entered middle school without years of English pre-study or long stays abroad. He was working, but a printed vocabulary book still left several tasks disconnected: seeing a word, knowing how it sounds, understanding it in a sentence, and retrieving it without a hint. A correct Korean translation did not always mean the word was available when he needed it.
docs/submission/DEVPOST_COPY.md:45:I found other Korean families facing the same gap. They did not need another instruction to “memorize harder.” They needed a way to see which connection was missing and to practice that connection often enough for the word to become usable.
docs/submission/DEVPOST_COPY.md:51:A learner can begin with a free diagnostic without creating an account. The diagnostic checks 20 words and can add five focused questions when one connection is especially weak.
docs/submission/DEVPOST_COPY.md:53:15Loop measures four connections:
docs/submission/DEVPOST_COPY.md:58:4. **Active recall:** retrieve the missing word from a meaning and sentence cue.
docs/submission/DEVPOST_COPY.md:60:The result does not label a child as “bad at vocabulary.” It shows the connection that should be strengthened first. A parent can then attach that result to a child profile and continue with a seven-day open-beta program built around 15 minutes of active learning per day.
docs/submission/DEVPOST_COPY.md:62:During continued learning, 15Loop stores connection scores, word mastery, review intervals, and due times. Its adaptive queue gives priority to overdue weak words, then due-soon words, then unseen words. Missed items return after other questions instead of repeating immediately. The goal is not a fixed number of words; it is the number of distinct words the learner actually reconnects during 15 focused minutes.
docs/submission/DEVPOST_COPY.md:70:- a no-sign-up adaptive diagnostic;
docs/submission/DEVPOST_COPY.md:72:- parent-owned accounts with up to three child profiles;
docs/submission/DEVPOST_COPY.md:76:- four-connection progress data and parent reporting;
docs/submission/DEVPOST_COPY.md:77:- a private five-word friend challenge without public rankings or child identity;
docs/submission/DEVPOST_COPY.md:79:- privacy-conscious analytics that exclude child names, answers, studied words, and account identifiers.
docs/submission/DEVPOST_COPY.md:81:The public beta currently uses a human-reviewed 30-word learning set. A larger curriculum map and candidate catalog are kept behind review and publication gates rather than being exposed automatically.
docs/submission/DEVPOST_COPY.md:85:GPT-5.6 is used at runtime where simple string matching is not enough: evaluating a learner's optional original sentence or semantic recall response.
docs/submission/DEVPOST_COPY.md:95:I supplied the founder story, learner problem, product priorities, Korean parent perspective, and final product decisions. Codex helped turn those decisions into a working system: the learning state machine, bilingual interface, adaptive queue, D1 schema and APIs, authentication flow, GPT-5.6 evaluator, safety constraints, automated tests, mobile fixes, analytics, SEO foundations, deployment, and handoff documentation.
docs/submission/DEVPOST_COPY.md:97:Codex also accelerated review cycles. We inspected real mobile screenshots, changed recall from a burdensome full-sentence requirement to a word-focused cloze with an optional AI sentence challenge, made the free diagnostic the first guest experience, and verified the production path with automated and live checks.
docs/submission/DEVPOST_COPY.md:105:Saving scores was not enough. The product promise became real only when due time, mastery, and the learner's weakest connection changed the next queue. We built and tested an adaptive priority model that keeps the session finite and prevents the same missed word from appearing immediately again.
docs/submission/DEVPOST_COPY.md:109:Our first recall interaction asked learners to write too much. A real child interpreted the four repeated stages as the whole product and found the last step heavy. We changed the primary recall task to one missing word, kept listening and the complete sentence visible after success, and moved open-ended sentence generation into an optional GPT-5.6 challenge.
docs/submission/DEVPOST_COPY.md:111:### The product serves children, but the account belongs to a parent
docs/submission/DEVPOST_COPY.md:113:We separated the learner's low-friction first experience from parental identity and consent. The child can try the diagnostic without an email or password; continued records are attached only after a parent signs in, confirms guardian consent, and creates the child profile.
docs/submission/DEVPOST_COPY.md:118:- Made the diagnostic available before sign-up while preserving a parent-owned data model.
docs/submission/DEVPOST_COPY.md:125:The most useful question is not “Does the learner know this word?” It is “Which connection to this word is available, and which one disappears under pressure?”
docs/submission/DEVPOST_COPY.md:131:After the hackathon, we will run the open beta with Korean families, measure completion and repeat use before claiming learning outcomes, expand the learner-visible vocabulary only after human review, and validate whether parents will pay for continued 15-minute practice. Payment, public rankings, pronunciation scoring, and broad curriculum expansion are intentionally outside this submission.
docs/submission/DEVPOST_COPY.md:135:The repository history begins with the working MVP on July 15, 2026 and records meaningful additions during the submission period, including the adaptive review engine, production authentication, data-integrity controls, GPT-5.6 evaluation hardening, the open-beta diagnostic funnel, mobile optimization, analytics, and search infrastructure.
lib/supabase-browser.ts:5:export const authNextStorageKey = "15loop:auth-next";
docs/submission/JUDGE_TESTING.md:14:### 1. Start the free diagnostic
docs/submission/JUDGE_TESTING.md:17:2. The site should route to the public diagnostic landing page.
docs/submission/JUDGE_TESTING.md:19:4. Choose the free diagnostic action.
docs/submission/JUDGE_TESTING.md:21:Expected result: the learner enters the diagnostic without Google login, email, a password, or payment details.
docs/submission/JUDGE_TESTING.md:23:### 2. Exercise the four connections
docs/submission/JUDGE_TESTING.md:29:- sentence context → word;
docs/submission/JUDGE_TESTING.md:34:The diagnostic contains 20 questions. When a connection score is 60 or below, it can add five focused questions. A normal full run takes approximately 8–12 minutes.
docs/submission/JUDGE_TESTING.md:38:Complete the diagnostic and inspect the result.
docs/submission/JUDGE_TESTING.md:40:Expected result: 15Loop displays four connection scores, identifies the first connection to strengthen, and explains the finding without claiming to predict school grades. The next action offers to connect the result to a parent account.
docs/submission/JUDGE_TESTING.md:44:Continued records belong to a parent-owned account. Parent authentication supports Google OAuth and email magic links. A parent can confirm guardian consent, create up to three child profiles, and attach the pre-sign-up diagnostic to one child.
docs/submission/JUDGE_TESTING.md:46:No payment is required during the seven-day open beta, and no automatic charge is created.
docs/submission/JUDGE_TESTING.md:48:If a judge does not want to create an account, the public diagnostic is the complete credential-free judging route. The demo video shows the parent transition, adaptive 15-minute session, and GPT-5.6 evaluation.
docs/submission/JUDGE_TESTING.md:54:For a saved learner, the server builds the session queue from the learner's connection scores and word-review state. It prioritizes overdue weak words, then due-soon words, then unseen words. Missed words return after other items rather than repeating immediately.
docs/submission/JUDGE_TESTING.md:58:After a correct cloze recall during continued learning, open the optional sentence challenge and submit a short original sentence using the target word.
docs/submission/JUDGE_TESTING.md:73:- Do not enter a real child's name, school, email, or personal story.
docs/submission/JUDGE_TESTING.md:75:- The evaluation prompt does not include a parent email or child profile name.
docs/submission/JUDGE_TESTING.md:77:- The diagnostic is a learning-connection tool, not a prediction of grades or a professional educational assessment.
docs/submission/JUDGE_TESTING.md:102:For a judging-access problem, contact the entrant through the Devpost submission profile. Do not send child learning data in a support request.
